2026-07-19 09:24:00 PDT — Issue #7 investigation started

Observed behavior
- A press/click on the rendered scene could immediately point the camera away from the bridge.
- Pointer lock and pointer capture were already absent, so the regression was in camera rotation math.

Root-cause analysis (5 whys)
1. A click appeared to reset the view because the first pointer movement changed orientation dramatically.
2. Browsers can emit a tiny pointermove between press and release without an intentional drag.
3. The handler immediately assigned camera.rotation.order = "YXZ".
4. Direct Euler-order assignment reinterprets existing angle components instead of preserving the current quaternion.
5. Camera-order initialization was mixed into movement handling, with no threshold separating clicks from drags.

2026-07-19 09:28:00 PDT — Test-first failure confirmed
- Added regression requirements for an intentional-drag threshold and orientation-preserving Euler reorder.
- The test failed against the deployed implementation for the expected missing safeguards.

Root-cause correction
- Replaced direct Euler-order assignment with rotation.reorder("YXZ"), which preserves orientation.
- Added a four-pixel intentional-drag threshold.
- Kept natural press-drag-release behavior with pointer up, cancel, and leave stopping the drag.
- Did not add pointer lock or pointer capture.

2026-07-19 09:34:45 PDT — Validation passed
- npm run lint: PASS
